    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1518517435,
    "last_edit_date" : 1518517435,
    "creation_date" : 1408534446,
    "answer_id" : 25403629,
    "question_id" : 3402735,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I discovered that the accepted answer actually doesn't always work, because <code>\\\\Z</code> may occur in the file. Another problem is that if you don't have the correct charset a whole bunch of unexpected things may happen which may cause the scanner to read only a part of the file.</p>\n\n<p>The solution is to use a delimiter which you are certain will never occur in the file. However, this is theoretically impossible. What we CAN do, is use a delimiter that has such a small chance to occur in the file that it is negligible: such a delimiter is a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universally_unique_identifier\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">UUID</a>, which is natively supported in Java.</p>\n\n<pre><code>String content = new Scanner(file, \"UTF-8\")\n    .useDelimiter(UUID.randomUUID().toString()).next();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
